{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-11-22","name":"Anketil de St. Medard","nameForms":[{"lang":"und","fullText":"Anketil de St. Medard","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Anketil"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"de St. Medard"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"1100–1146","fullLifespan":"about 1100–after 1146","birthDate":"+1100","birthPlace":{"address":"Thornhaugh, Northamptonshire, England","geo":{"latitude":52.58915,"longitude":-0.43889,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1146","deathPlace":{"address":"Northamptonshire, England","geo":{"latitude":52.35,"longitude":-0.85,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"\"The first Medard at Thornhaugh early 1100 was a Ansketil of Medard. We also know that the Medards were linked to the Abbot of Peterborough Abbey.  The above villages are known holdings by 1146.\nFIRST GENERATION\nAnketil De St Medard  living in 1146.  In the bull of Pope Eugenius, dated in 1146, the fee of Anketil, of St Medard, in Thornhaw, Wettering, Sibberton, Angoteby, and Etton, with their apprentices, was confirmed, amongst many other possessions, to the abbey of Burgh.\nThis is the first account of Thornhaw Lordship, no mention of it in the Domesday Survey.\nLands included;\nTen hides, and three parts of one rood in Northamptonshire\nThree Carucates in Angoteby in Lincolnshire\nAnketil De St Medard had the following children:   +2      i.    Richard De St Medard.\n            +3             ii.    Girard De St Medard.\nhttp://www.cb5.co.uk/StMedard1.htm","sourceList":[{"title":"Victoria County History of Northamptonshire, Volume V, ed. Philip Riden & Charles Insley, 2002, online at www.british-his","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceUri":"9LRF-YF5"}],"events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1100","date":"about 1100","place":"Thornhaugh, Northamptonshire, England"},{"name":"Death","sources":"1","year":"1146","date":"after 1146","place"